segments.text: In fact, he even suggested, which let everybody know he was serious, why don't we just really curtail admissions to the College of Engineering until we get them some more space.
What was their reaction to that proposal?
Not too good.
They wanted things to keep growing.
And I think some had visions that someday we might catch up to the University of Texas.
I keep worrying that that is their goal.
If you could determine the enrollment in engineering here without having to explain it to anyone, what total would you set?
You mean now?
On now?
I wouldn't have it quite as high as it is now.
I wouldn't either.
Now, that would mean I wouldn't have to explain it to the voter because that would be very difficult.
Are there other regents that were also strong supporters of Renzi?
Well, there were ones thinking about it, but they never verbally supported it strongly.
But, of course, I left the room, there was lots of discussion, and then they got Mr. Powell,

from the physical plan in they started talking about things as a result of that you can almost count the buildings around here you know this building engineering physics building uh... that new petroleum building the new building that's uh... for aerospace computing and so forth quite a few popped up but i think space is still a little bit of a problem because
Were there some important gifts, either equipment or funding, during those years?
Well, probably one of the biggest gifts that helped a lot was from Mr. Zachary on computing.
He thought we ought to be up-to-date in computing, and so he made several significant discs.
Now, was that H.B.
Zachary?
Yeah, Pat Zachary.
Pat Zachary.
Yeah.
Let's see, any legislators that you remember as being helpful?
No, there were never any problems, but nobody that really stood up and hollered for us or anything like that.
During your years as dean, what relations, if any, did you have with the University of Texas Engineering program?
Oh, I knew Dean Goyna over there very well.
What's his name?
Goyna was dean of engineering.
G-L-O-Y-N-A?
G-L-O-Y-N-A, Goyna.
And he was dean of engineering.

In fact, he sent me a congratulation note as soon as it came out that I was dean here and we had meetings together and the deans of the Texas engineering schools met at least once a year, sometimes more, compared our notes on things.
But the relationship with the University of Texas and engineering were very good.
So there was no problem there.
Lots of cooperation.
Which of the engineering programs in the state, for which did you have the highest regard?
I'm not going to ask the negative.
It's hard to say.

I think before I came here I would have said when I was in New Jersey I probably would have said Rice University because it's had such a good standard and controls the enrollment with the resources and so forth.
But I found
A lot of them were doing a good job, so I didn't have a leader or anything.
During your dean years, some key faculty appointments that you look back upon with pride?
Did we bring any new key folks?
Oh, well, there's so many, but screened them very carefully, and everybody that got in that got through the dean's office was well qualified, I think, so didn't have any problems that way.
mention a bunch of names, but they're all doing well.
Of course, I was really pleased when we had this tall young man from Kansas that wanted to be a faculty member here after he got his degree, and that was Bud Peterson.
I don't know whether you ever encountered him, but he
Turned out very well in mechanical engineering, actually, although I wasn't at that time.
I was over in the dean's office, and I remember having some fun with him because he had a little error in his resume, and I asked him about that.
But anyway, he became department head here after a few years.
Then he was an associate dean over in the dean's office here, and last year he left and went up to RPI as the provost.
So he's moving right along.
Very good.
Summarize these, this list you gave, summarize those accomplishments.
Well, I thought that, I hadn't mentioned it in detail to you, but I did implement an enrollment management plan.
We just couldn't have the students coming in, flooding in like that.
How did it
Well, it worked.
There were a lot of parts to it.
One was admission criteria at the freshman level went up.
The transfer students coming in at the junior level, we made that pretty difficult, too.
Otherwise, there was a way they could make an end run around that.
And then retention.
And retention, that happened at the end of the sophomore level, whether it could go on into the junior or senior year or transferring to some other college, whatever they wish.
And that worked very well.
I forget what I called it.
I made one mistake when I first presented it.
I had to have the approval of the Board of Regents.
I forget what I called it.
I should remember that, but they didn't like that at all.
Then I went back and called it an enrollment management plan.
Well, that was okay.
So anyway, that went through.

And of course, we were very active at that time in engineering, recruiting National Merit Scholars, because I found that every one you brought in, there were other students in the school that came along.
So it really helped us.
And in 1982, we had 189 of them.
And then we started up computer science, I mentioned, and got the graduate enrollment going along, introduced computer-aided instruction in pilot courses then.
And then I had an assistant dean, Terry Schau,
who also is somebody that I hired once before in the East, and he was down in Houston.
I brought him in, and he had a very skillful way of handling minorities, and he started up summer enrichment programs for minorities to get them in here.
In that case, he was bringing in high school seniors or juniors and got them interested.
Many of them came back later.
And he also, he started up the first...
I think it was called the Black Engineering Society, and gave them a charge.
Their charge was to take the incoming blacks, African Americans, and make sure that they worked, stayed in school.
So that turned out to be very good.
So that helped on the student side.
And of course, as far as what they were taking, the curriculum, all of our programs went through accreditation well.
Engineering Technology was an interesting program to me because when I first came here, it seemed to be

getting a lot of funding was different than a lot of schools and was handled on about the same level as every engineering program whereas most schools considered it a little bit different type and didn't require all the resources that the others did but anyway we restructured those programs started up a department of computer science and asked each department to set its five-year program goals for five years so that helped a lot
And then with the faculty, of course, I developed a new committee structure for the college.
I actually put out booklets so they knew who was doing what and the charge for each committee was there.
and put out new guidelines for promotion and tenure because they didn't exist.
Had a little fuss with the T's, the people on that, the head of T's, Porter, because he wanted to know the dollar amount of every research account that came in.
I said, no, I just want to know if they got support and in what area.
The forms were made out that way.
We got these mid-year salary increases that I mentioned.
And then with the computer, we got new computer equipment.
Fortunately, we got outside funding to pay for that.
And then I made a study, which it turned out... Don't worry.
No problem.
It turned out that...

I studied what we had in terms of dollars here for equipment and then compared that to some national information I had and then the other Texas deans got involved and we calculated up for the whole state.
And then I wrote a short note which appeared in American Society of Engineering Education.
So then we had a $1 billion shortage for the state of Texas.
And then the legislature got busy on that.
And I was no longer dean when the money started coming through.
But money came through for equipment funds and so forth to bring us up to date.
And while I was here, of course, we had national meetings here.
I got the Engineering Council for Professional Development for accreditation to meet here.
We had the ASE annual conference, American Society of Engineering Education.
That was in 82.
Brought a lot of people to campus which wouldn't normally have come here.
And then we started a memorandum of agreement with a German university where I knew some people.
So we started exchanging some students, had their faculty coming over here.
It's been very productive over the years and worked out very well.
In fact, many faculties told me that they liked having those German students in their graduate classes because it showed the American students what kind of competition they'd be up against.
Of course, they were carefully selected by this German university to be the best, but that worked out well.
And then we started an alumni honors program, which I mentioned to you earlier, and we had an engineering development council, which involved off-campus people.

and I was surprised there were no annual reports or anything for the College of Engineering that could be circulated nationally because I was used to in most cases in the past I'd always get a few annual reports from leading colleges of engineering so we produced the first report of the college
And we decided it was quite an effort to do it and do all the other things while we do it every two years.
So two of those reports went out while I was dean on a national mailing basis.
Nice color brochures showing what we were doing, what was up to date, and so forth.
And then the last item, one that I wanted to mention, was they started an engineering industry teaching program to bring practitioners onto campus.
And this was also through the help of Pat Zachary.

He funded some money, something special thing where he had made some money in South America, and he endowed that so that we'd have money to bring somebody in from industry for a few weeks or longer and participate in our program to give more of the industrial flavor to the students and faculty.
And I thought that was very good.
As you look back on those years, can you think of any opportunities that we missed, oversight?
No, I can't really.
As I said, when I came here, one of the things that attracted me was the challenge.
I knew there was a lot to be done, and it kept me busy, and I ended up with an exceptionally good team in my office.
I kept referring to it as a basketball team.
You didn't have to look before you threw the ball.
They all knew what they were supposed to do.
So I'd say no opportunities that we really missed.
Describe, if there was such, describe a typical day for the Dean of Engineering during that time.
What time did you get here and normally what kinds of activities would the dean have to get involved in?
Yeah, I wish there was a typical day, but I don't recall that there was one, but I always got here very early in the morning.
I'd be in before the secretaries like quarter of eight or something like that and see what was laying on the desk.
But then the day would be very full.
I tried to get out of the office a lot and visit the other departments because only some of the departments at that time were in the Zachary Building and see what was going on.
have a lot of paperwork to take care of because due to some strange circumstances, for a while we did not have any sort of a financial helper in the dean's office.
We had a Mr. Fenner who did a good job, but then he was unhappy that the reorganization wasn't being carried out to improve, so he left.
So we had to do that ourselves.
I had to work it out with some secretaries and make sure that all the proper financial forms were filled out and handled so that the money was spent properly and appropriately.
So that kept me busy.

going on to a typical day, there'd always be some people to meet with, and I gave the secretary, my secretary, blocks of time where she could schedule people, but there were other blocks where she could not because I had to get work done.
But I'd keep working, and it'd usually be 7.30 or 8 o'clock at night before I'd go home and then have dinner with my wife.
How often did you get a call from a board, directly from a regent?
I don't think I ever did.
Legislator?
No, never got a direct call like that.
I often got direct calls from newspaper people.
About what?
Oh, about anything that they thought might be worth the media getting involved in.
You're meaning reporters?
Yeah, reporters, right.
But there were no big...
There was no big pressure coming the other way.
No big front page story?
No, no.
And no catastrophes, accidents?
during those years were there?
No, no.
I was lucky that way.
How much time did you have to spend out of town?
How much time on the road?
Well, I would say four or five days every month, something like that.
There were contacts I had to make on behalf of the college, fortunately a lot of them in Texas and Dallas or San Antonio.
San Antonio was a hard place to get to because it takes time, but then Houston.

But also in New York City and I went out to Seattle quite a bit because I had some other friends in Boeing out there and the University of Washington and I got Boeing to make some contributions at the right time when we needed things, so that helped out.

In a way, I didn't spend too much time away, but here was very, very challenging and sometimes very tiring because what schedule I told you, that held six days a week, except on the sixth day there weren't any secretaries around, so I could really get through a lot of that mail that piled up.
Unfortunately, or fortunately, I don't know, I had a secretary that was brand new.

and I had trouble teaching her between to make piles you know things that had to be taken care of right away things that could wait a little bit and things that were absolutely junk mail but uh... so I tackled some of those piles
but the junk mail and the other stuff sometimes wait till Saturday when it could just tear through that stuff.
During those leadership years, what were some of the high points, the most proud moments?

Well, I think that one of the ones was when we have a group like the Board of Directors of the Accreditation Board, the National Accreditation Board, beat here, and we have them here for a couple days to see directly what's going on, and they're liking things.
That's good.
And also when we had the American Society for Engineering Education here, Jim Earl did the main job of arranging everything.
I don't recall the number, but we probably had about 1,500 or 2,000 educators from around the United States here at that time.
And that did us a lot of good.
Every year after that, I'd bump into somebody who said, oh, down at A&M, that was so good.
They stayed in the dorms and we had lots of student activity.
The students were typical Aggies, very kind to everybody.
The students ran buses for them around campus where they had to go.
Lots of good friendships developed.
Do you remember, did the dean ever get victimized by any kind of Aggie joke, Aggie prank?
No, if he did, I didn't hear him.
They kept it away from me, I guess.
No, I never heard of anything of that sort.
Of course, every dean hears a dean's jokes, but that's just normal procedure.
Sure, sure.
As you then finished your term as dean, where were we best and where were we not as good as you wanted us to be?
Well, we still hadn't, of course, since it takes time to build buildings, we hadn't solved the space problem at all.
And we were still short on faculty.
The teaching loads were too high, and that definitely was not good.
What we were best, though, was that we had a faculty that was pretty enthusiastic and highly motivated.
I tried to talk to them a lot.
keep them informed on where we were heading and see if they agreed to be heading there.
And I think I got very good cooperation from them.
All right, now I've just about run out of thoughts about questions.
What have we not covered?
You didn't have an illness problem.
No.
So nothing like that.
No, I grabbed some stuff before I left here.
We covered the
And the enrollment, you mentioned the enrollment went up and research volume went up.
During those years, what did you and your wife do for relaxation?
What were your favorite avocations?
Well, it was kind of difficult because, as you know, Dean keeps busy.
But the prime thing for us was to make sure that we got together with the family, usually at holidays like Christmas holiday.
The first Christmas we were here, I think all the children came in.
And then as they got children themselves, they started to alternate because they wanted Christmas at home or at the other side of the family.

and of course the first Christmas here I always remember that was interesting because after we had all these guests in then a couple times we thought we'd go out to eat but at that time all the restaurants were closed in town because the students were away and not many people were staying in town then except a few foreign students so that became a problem but that's all changed now now did y'all have a key church home here yes we did yeah
A church home?
Yes.
Yeah, well, our Savior's Lutheran Church.
And you were Lutherans before you got here?
We were Lutherans before we got here, yeah.
And we checked it out when we came down here and looked around and so forth.
And who have been your closest personal friends?
Uh...
That's hard to say.
I had a lot of good friends.
I think probably when Skip Fletcher came on board since he was the associate dean, probably the closest.
Okay, then as I get near the end, if you were brought in as the hired consultant,
to advise Texas A&M's decision makers today about the College of Engineering, what advice would you give them?
Assuming that there are no restraints on the advice you could offer.
I probably would hit on the same thing that I watched over the years and that is the space for faculty.
and classrooms and so forth.
We need to, obviously, we need to modernize classrooms and things like that.
But, for example, right next door here, two people use that office.
One is former director of the Johnson Space Center, Aaron Cullen.
Same size as this one.
Because there are more offices available.
So, and I think
a serious faculty member that wants to do a good job, he ought to have a nice private office where he can.
What about organizational structure?
Would you have any advice about?
No.
The way it sits here, I guess it's fairly well organized in terms of departments and so forth.
Some schools have tried to give that up, but I think you could do, as far as curriculum goes, you could do a lot more with the freshman year and so forth than we do now.
How so?

Well, I think you ought to make it more of a self-speed learning experience rather than formal instruction because a lot of the students are ready to do that, where they become the one that decides how fast they learn.
That can be done by the right kind of lecture techniques or by computers.
There are lots of ways to do it, but let them move as fast as they want.
Would you have any advice about enrollment size for the college?
Too big.
Too big for the faculty and resources.
What number would you suggest they consider?
Well, I'd say probably around 8,000 would be fine, yeah.
And instead of 10?
Instead of 10, something where they are now, yeah.
Would you have limits for each of the majors in that eight?
Yeah, I think it should be...
keep them comparable in size so that the person, you wouldn't have one department that's dominating.
What about the relative emphasis of the undergraduate and the graduate?
Well, I think that
We really ought to put more emphasis on graduate right now than we are doing because in today's world, you almost need that master's degree, period.
PhD is not essential for everybody by any means, but master's is getting almost essential.
And the administrative organizational structure, what would be the relationship with the dean and the experiment station?
I don't know.
Well, I like the kind of arrangement they have now where there's one dean that has all that under control.

but like and you've been president and administrator at many levels I think that sometime rather we've got to measure not only the student-faculty ratio but the student-administrator ratio and administrators have grown like mad and
For example, when I was dean, we started up this program with Germany, an exchange program for faculty and students, ran smooth, never got money from anywhere else or anything like that.
Now, I don't know, we've gotten this associate provost, I guess,

international fairs couple of assistant provosts for the same thing you know and it seems like we have a lot of people there now why is that a problem well of course it takes resources but also the faculty get tired of getting these questionnaires from some provost that has minimum responsibilities and must want to fill up a file cabinet or something with returns I would check that student administrative ratio
Do you have any engineering programs in mind that would be possibly good models for Texas A&M?
Who are some other schools that we might want to?
Well, those do change rather rapidly, but as the different programs have been reviewed around the country, I thought Duke was headed in the right direction as far as their engineering program goes.
Although the first time I reviewed them, I came down hard on them because they weren't using computers in their classroom.
That's some time ago, you know, and not putting enough emphasis on it.
Well, that's all been changed.
What about among the land-grant schools?
Among the land-grant schools?
I just visited last week up at State College, Pennsylvania.
About the same size as us now.
I was surprised, 44,000 on that campus, on the main campus.
They seem to be very well organized, very well organized, and doing well in many of their programs, yeah.
We used them as one of our models in the early 60s when we were dreaming of what A&M might become.
They had already moved.
They and Michigan State, and they were two of our college models.
Let's see.
What administrator or administrators would you want to say thank you, express appreciation to?
Mike Prescott.
No question about it.
In fact, he wrote a little book.
I don't know whether I can put my little pamphlet on about quality in the academic atmosphere.
Once in a while I pull that out and show it to people.
I think it's over there somewhere, a little pamphlet.
But I think he did a lot for the university.
You know you worked closely with him.
Every chance he had, he had people remembering that we were going for quality here.
We weren't second rate.
All right, then my last question would be what feelings do you have in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Oh, very strong.
I'm up at the Notre Dame game with a couple of my, well, I should say with two sons, two son-in-laws.
No, I feel very strong about that.
I'm a converted Aggie, I guess.
All right, let's quit with that then.
When it has no sound, it stops?
Yes.
It has sound.
One more time.
It has that.
